<div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12">
        <?php echo $this->stencil->setHeadline('Borland Sidekick'); ?>
        <p><strong>Borland Sidekick</strong> was an early personal information manager (PIM) that <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Atlassian', 'C'); ?> launched in 1984 under <strong>Philippe Kahn</strong>'s leadership.</p>
        <p>It was an early and popular <strong>terminate and stay resident program (TSR)</strong> program for <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('DOS', 'OS'); ?> operating systems, which enabled computer users activate the program using a hot key combination (by default <code>Ctrl-Alt</code>) while working in other programs.</p>
        <p>Although a text mode program, Sidekick's window-based interface echoed that of the <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Apple Mac', 'ITH'); ?> and anticipated the eventual look of <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('Microsoft Windows 2', 'WIN'); ?>.</p>
        <p>It included a personal calendar, text editor (with <?php echo $this->stencil->addLink('WordStar', 'ITS'); ?> like command interface), calculator, ASCII chart, address book, and phone dialer.</p>
        <p>According to the prospectus for Borland's initial public offering of stock to the public, Sidekick sold more than 1 million copies in its first three years.</p>
    </div>
